notes.note: This course aims to help the students to learn the most commonly used advanced control methodologies and their applications to practical systems. It covers several powerful control methodologies and their applications in a brief way. The methodologies include Linear Quadratic Optimal Control, Model Predictive Control, Optimal H-infinity Control, Tracking Control, Disturbance Observer, Iterative Learning Control, System Identification, and Adaptive Control, as well as some nonlinear control techniques such as Gain Scheduling, Feedback Linearization, and Sliding Mode Control. Practical examples including autonomous vehicles, suspension systems, quadrotors, and manipulators, will be introduced to students in terms of homework and course projects. Both MAE 443/543 and MAE 571 are required as prerequisites.

The mechanical and other physical properties of materials can be dramatically different when the characteristic dimensions of the system are confined to small length-scales below 100 nm. These size-scale effects in mechanics result from the enhanced role of surfaces and interfaces, defects and material variations, and quantum effects. Understanding of the fundamental nanomechanics and the manipulating of those phenomena are key to the application of advanced manufacturing (AM), micro-electro-mechanical (MEMS) or nano-electro-mechanical (NEMS) fabrication, lubricant industries, surface and interface engineering, soft/miniaturized robotics, biomechanical materials/devices etc. This course will have a focus on fundamentals and applications of atomic/molecular interactions, phonon, contact mechanics, nano-tribology, and scanning probe microscopy (SPM) system.

MAE509.title: Special Topics
MAE509.alt_title: Quant of Uncert in Phys Models

notes.note: This course provides an introduction to the basic concepts and methods of physics-based predictive computational modeling of complex physical systems in the face of uncertainty. Topics include frequentists and logical probability theories; Global sensitivity analyses; Bayesian methods for model calibration, validation, and selection; Information theory and maximum entropy; Monte Carlo computational methods; and example applications in nano-/micro-scale materials, multi-species biological systems, and other physical systems.

catalog.title: Computational Fluid Dynamics 1
catalog.description: This course is intended for seniors and beginning graduate students interested in computer based analysis of engineering problems in fluid mechanics and heat transfer. Students need not have a graduate level background in fluid mechanics or heat transfer, however, an undergraduate level is necessary. The general governing equations of fluid mechanics and heat transfer and methods to solve them, that will mainly focus on finite-difference and finite-volume methods. Topics on the classification and analysis of these methods are examined with application to conduction heat transfer, convection and laminar mixing problems. The overall objective of this course is to provide the student with a firm understanding of the fundamentals of CFD employed in many commercial packages and an introduction to computer tools for analysis and graphical representation of results.

notes.note: Students will apply knowledge of fluid mechanics, heat transfer, and thermodynamics towards the design of fluid-thermal systems. Given design goals and a concept design, students will break complex systems down into sub-systems, develop fluid-thermal models for the sub-systems, then apply optimization schemes to produce an optimized design. It is strongly recommended that students have taken or are taking Fluid Mechanics, Thermodynamics, and Heat Transfer alongside this course.

Spacecraft Structures and Design 
the second graduate course in advanced aerospace structures, focusing on the understanding of the design elements involved in developing spacecraft, space modules or space vehicles. It offers graduate students with an opportunity to study and learn the fundamentals of spacecraft structural analysis and design. As part of this course, a number of key techniques for determining stress in spacecraft components will be discussed. Students will be guided through the process of analyzing, sizing and preliminary designing of piloted reentry vehicle structures. The topics provide an overview of the structural requirements critical to engineers involved in spacecraft development. The topics discussed as part of this course, and its prerequisite Advanced Aerostructures, are essential to the practice of aircraft and space development.

MAE527 is an applied pattern recognition course with emphasizes on human computer interactions. The main objective of this course is to use novel and natural modalities such as sketching, gestures, and brain activity to interact with a machine/computer. Although the application of this course is focused on CAD interfaces, the concepts covered in the class can be also applied to human activity recognitions, human centered design, and human machine interactions in general.

catalog.title: Nano/Microtechnologies MEMS
catalog.description: Introduces advanced technologies that enable integration of micro-sensors and micromechanical components on the same chip to produce miniature devices called micro electromechanical systems (MEMS). The course covers physical principles and design rules that govern the performance of a device at small length scales. Discuss a large set of microfabrication techniques including photolithography, material removal processes, and additive technologies. Discuss the applications of MEMS devices in automotive, communication, energy, and BioMEMS in biomedical applications.

catalog.title: Materials Experimental Methods
catalog.description: This lecture course will cover experimental methods in materials science and engineering. These methods will relate to the characterization of material structures (using spectroscopy, microscopy and diffraction techniques), material properties (mechanical, thermal, electrical, electrochemical, etc.) and material processes (phase transformations, reactions, diffusion, etc.).  Illustrations will be made using materials including metals, ceramics, polymers, carbons, semiconductors and composites. This course is dual-listed with MAE 489.

This course is targeted at senior Ph.D. students and Masters students (approval from instructor is required) who are already experienced with the basics of machine learning and robotic algorithms. The goal of this course is to introduce students to a wide array of machine learning algorithms for generating, mainly neural network-based, control and planning models needed by a single autonomous agent or a team of agents. We will mainly consider the broad class of problem settings where optimum decisions are not known a priori and are instead learnt through trial episodes, which can be loosely termed as reinforcement learning or RL. While a summary background of RL and related basics (e.g., Markov Decision Processes) will be covered in the form of lectures early in the course, the focus will be on student-driven learning of different advanced RL and related algorithms (e.g., neuroevolution) and their state-of-the-art implementations for solving real-world problems. We will also learn how to implement such algorithms for embodied robotic systems through interactions with robotic simulators and benchmarking environments such as the Open AI Gym. This course will also touch upon the emerging challenges related to generalizability and robustness of policies designed with such learning based approaches.

catalog.title: Robotics II
catalog.description: The objective of this course is to provide working knowledge required to formulate and analyze problems related to the application of collaborative robots. This course will also provide methodologies for solutions to such formulated problems. This course is dual-listed with MAE 490.
